        {
            "title": "DominAnts",
            "date": {
                "start": {
                    "month": 8,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2020
                },
                "end": {
                    "month": 9,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2020
                }
            },
            "description": "DominAnts is the first game projected, completed by me and a few other students for Saxion UAS. It is a turn-based strategy tabletop game for 2-4 players, in which every player controls an ant hive. The main game dynamics are gathering sugar cubes, to build an army of ants to gather even more of the former, or to upgrade it to fight other hives. The player who takes over all other players\u2019 hives becomes the winner.\nMy responsibilities were game systems and manual design. It was actually the first time that I (professionally) tackled a game, consisting of multiple complex systems \u2013 gathering, combat, troops, takeover and special events system, each with its own set of mechanics. A main takeaway for me from the project is how a change of a mechanic in a given system has an impact on other systems and general game experience. For instance, during the testing phase, one of the main problems that we encountered was the game taking too long to compete. To solve it, we analysed a few factors \u2013the map being too big, too harsh resource system, players \\ not taking initiative to fight. One of the measures we took was adding 3 startup upgraded troops for each player, with the intention of shortening the initial grinding to build an army. During the latter playtest, however, we realized that not only does it fulfil the task we had in mind, but also inclines players to take more aggressive actions, because they feel threatened by these more powerful troops (and therefore want them eliminated).\nLooking back on it, there are a few pitfalls in the overall design of the game, like e.g. the too complex combat system, which needed a ton of explanations in the manual and proved that it is hard to decide on the outcome of given situations. Overall, however, I am happy with how it turned out overall and that I managed to learn the importance of game systems early on.",
